{"title_page": "Peyami Safa", "text_new": "{{short description|Turkish writer and journalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Expand Turkish|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer  \n| name          = Peyami Safa\n| image         = Peyami Safa is working in Yedig\u00fcn.png\n| image_size    = 250 px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Peyami Safa is working in Yedig\u00fcn Magazine\n| pseudonym     = Server Bedi{{,}}\u00c7\u00f6mez{{,}}Ser\u00e2z\u00e2d{{,}}Safiye Peyman{{,}}Bedia Servet\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1899|4|2}}\n| birth_place   = [[Fatih]], [[Istanbul]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1961|6|15|1899|4|2}} \n| death_place   = [[Kad\u0131k\u00f6y]], Istanbul, Turkey\n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer{{,}}journalist\n| nationality   = Turkish\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     =\n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = 1910\u20131961\n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = [[Cing\u00f6z Recai]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Nebahat Erin\u00e7|1938}}\n| partner       = \n| children      = Merve Safa\n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Peyami Safa''' (April 2, 1899 \u2013 June 15, 1961) was a [[Index of Turkey biography-related articles|Turkish]] journalist, columnist and novelist. He came to the fore in the [[Turkish literature]] of the Republican era with his psychological works such as ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu'' (Ninth External Ward). He reflected his life and his changes to his works. He wrote many novels under the pseudonym ''Server Bedi''. He created the type ''Cing\u00f6z Recai'' inspired by [[Ars\u00e8ne Lupin]] of the French writer [[Maurice Leblanc]]. He also worked as a journalist at various institutions and published several magazines such as K\u00fclt\u00fcr Haftas\u0131 with his brother \u0130lhami Safa.\n\nThe poet [[Tevfik Fikret]] named him when he was born. After he lost his father at a young age, he lived under difficult conditions with his mother and brother. Bone tuberculosis appeared on the right arm. He processed his psychology in those years in his autobiographical novel, Ninth External Ward. He gave his first literary products during his education in [[Vefa High School]]. He worked as a teacher for a short time. The stories he published under the title ''Stories of the Century'' drew attention and received encouraging reactions. He entered pen quarrels with prominent literary writers of the period. He experienced various changes by exhibiting [[Positivism|positivist]], [[materialist]], [[mystical]], [[nationalist]], [[conservative]], [[anti-communist]] and [[corporatist]] attitudes. With his knowledge of [[French language|French]], he closely followed Western culture and innovations. In his early days, he made translations from names such as [[Maupassant]] and [[Rousseau]]. He always chose [[Istanbul]] as the venue for his later works and never gave up the synthesis and analysis of the East and the West. He published articles with critical style in newspapers such as [[Milliyet]]. His good relationships with [[N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]] and [[Necip Faz\u0131l K\u0131sak\u00fcrek]] turned into pen fights over time. At first, he became closer to the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]], then to the [[Democratic Party (Turkey, 1946)|Democratic Party]].\n\nHe continued his literary life, which he started at a young age, until his death. He was mainly [[nationalist]] and [[conservative]]. [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Ministry of National Education]] recommended his two books for secondary school students. His works were also adapted to the cinema and series in various periods.\n\n== Life ==\n=== Early life ===\n[[File:Peyami Safa's childhood photo for a magazine.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A childhood photo of Peyami Safa (1913)]]\nPeyami Safa was born on April 2, 1889 in Gedikpa\u015fa and named after Tevfik Fikret, one of the poets of [[Servet-i F\u00fcn\u00fbn]]. His father is \u0130smail Safa, who was referred to as a \"mother-born poet\" by [[Muallim Naci]] and belonging to a family of [[Trabzon]] origin. Her mother is Server Bedia Han\u0131m. Peyami Safa's father was one of the opponents of [[Abd\u00fclhamid II]] and died in [[Sivas]] while in exile without leaving anything financial to his family. <ref name=\":CB\u00dc\">{{Cite book |last1=Selim |first1=Alt\u0131ntop |last2=R\u0131za|first2=Ba\u011fc\u0131|last3=Can|first3=\u015een| title = Vefat\u0131n\u0131n 50. Y\u0131l\u0131nda Peyami Safa | url = http://en.sbe.cbu.edu.tr/db_images/site_1033/file/peyami_safa_kitabi.pdf |place= Manisa| publisher = Celal Bayar \u00dcniversitesi Sosyal Bilimler Enstit\u00fcs\u00fc | date = 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170202145309/http://en.sbe.cbu.edu.tr/db_images/site_1033/file/peyami_safa_kitabi.pdf | archive-date=2017}}</ref>  Peyami Safa, who lost his father when he was one and a half years old, was brought up by his mother under hard conditions with his brother Ilhami Safa. During his primary education, bone tuberculosis appeared in his right arm. Due to his illness, he could not attend school and found himself among doctors, patients and caregivers at a young age. He influenced the effect of this disease in his work, [[Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu]]. <ref name=\":Bilkent\">{{Cite web| last1 = Aksoy | first1 = S\u00fcreyya Elif |title = Peyami Safa Romanlar\u0131nda Modernle\u015fme ve Mekan | url = http://www.thesis.bilkent.edu.tr/0003885.pdf | publisher = [[Bilkent University]] | date = 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHe started his high school education in [[Vefa High School]] in [[Fatih]] in [[1910]]. During these years, he was a classmate with [[Ekrem Hakk\u0131 Ayverdi]] and [[Elif Naci]]. Also [[Hasan \u00c2li Y\u00fccel]] and [[Yusuf Ziya Orta\u00e7]] were among their high school friends. He gave his first literary discussions and products in those years. He wrote his first story essay ''Piano Teaching'' and his first novel essay ''Eski Dost'' in high school. In addition, the first story book titled ''Don't Take This Book'', which he published during these periods, aroused curiosity and sold out within a few days. <ref>{{cite book|last=G\u00f6ze|first=Ergun|title=Peyami Safa-Naz\u0131m Hikmet Kavgas\u0131|date=1963|location=\u0130stanbul|isbn=|page=42|publisher=Ya\u011fmur Yay\u0131nlar\u0131}}</ref>  He could not continue his high school education due to his illness and his family's livelihood problems.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ayvazo\u011flu|first=Be\u015fir|title=Peyami Hayat\u0131 Sanat\u0131 Felsefesi Dram\u0131|date=1998|location=\u0130stanbul|isbn=|page=37\u201354|publisher=[[\u00d6t\u00fcken Ne\u015friyat]]}}</ref> He developed the knowledge of [[French language|French]] by memorizing [[Petit Larousse]], a gift from his father's close friends, [[Abdullah Cevdet]], and began to be interested in [[medicine]], [[psychology]] and [[philosophy]] books besides literary works. Due to his interest in the [[theater]] in the future, he took the [[Dar\u00fclbedayi|D\u00e2r\u00fclbedayi]] exams but could not continue despite his success. During the times of [[the First World War]], he started working in the Post Office to help his mother. <ref name=\":A\u00dc\">{{Cite web| author = Ya\u015far \u00d6zkanda\u015f | title = Peyami Safa'n\u0131n D\u00fc\u015f\u00fcnceleri Ekseninde T\u00fcrk Modernle\u015fmesinin \u0130ncelenmesi | url = https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1Wt13HgwVD_UzZuUVA4bmFRZVk | publisher = [[Ankara University]] | date = 2016}}</ref> Later, he was appointed as a teacher to the Rehber-i \u0130ttihad School in Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i (1917) and worked for a while in the [[D\u00fcyun-u Umumiye|D\u00fcy\u00fbn-\u0131 Um\u00fbmiye Administration]] (1918).<ref name=\":TDV\u0130A\">{{cite encyclopedia |author-link=[[Be\u015fir Ayvazo\u011flu]] |encyclopedia= TDV \u0130sl\u00e2m Ansiklopedisi |title=Safa, Peyami |url= |language= Turkish | date=2008 |publisher= Turkey Diyanet Foundation |volume=35 |location= \u0130stanbul |isbn=978-975-389-457-9 |oclc= |doi= |page=437\u2013440 |ref= }}</ref>\n\n=== Armistice and the Republican Era ===\n{{Cquote|These stories then gained a great success among the public, which still amazed me. The young literature of that time encouraged me fervently, asking me to sign my stories. [[Yakup Kadri Karaosmano\u011flu|Yakup Kadri]] says, \"You brought us a style,\" [[Yahya Kemal]] said, \"Peyami is the most beautiful work of Ismail Safa\". [7]|source= Peyami Safa, after his stories, which he published under the title ''Y\u00fczy\u0131l\u0131n Hik\u00e2yeleri'' (\"Stories of the Century\"), attracted attention.|float=right |width=30%}}\nPeyami Safa, who left his teaching position at the Rehber-i \u0130ttihad School during the armistice period in [[1918]], started publishing the newspaper Twentieth Century (Yirminci Y\u00fczy\u0131l) with his brother. In this newspaper, he drew attention with the stories he published under the heading \"Stories of the Century\". [8] He also made his first pen fight against [[Cenap \u015eahabettin]]'s adaptation play (1919). When he received a degree in the story contest organized by Alemdar newspaper, he was encouraged to write by the leading writers of the period. After ''Yirminci Y\u00fczy\u0131l'' was closed, they lasted his profession in journalism in places such as [[Terc\u00fcman-\u0131 Hakikat]] and [[Tasvir-i Efkar|Tasvir-i Efk\u00e2r]] (1922) after the declaration of the Republic. In addition, he published his first novel, ''[[S\u00f6zde K\u0131zlar]]'' (So-called Girls), for his livelihood. By [[1924]], He published his several works including ''Mah\u015fer'', ''Bir Gece'' (One Evening), ''S\u00fcng\u00fclerin G\u00f6lgesinde'' (In the Shadow of the Bayonets) and ''Istanbul Hikayeleri'' (the Stories of Istanbul). [9] In [[1925]], he published a short-lived newspaper called B\u00fcy\u00fck Yol with [[Halil L\u00fctf\u00fc D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc]]. Also in these years, he wrote in [[Cumhuriyet]] newspaper with the signature of \"Server Bedi\" and \"Peyami Safa\". He went on his relationship with the newspaper as a columnist and literature manager (1928-1940). His article titled \"New Literary Circles\" published in Hilal-i Ahmer magazine led to a pencil fight with [[Ahmet Ha\u015fim]] (1928). [10]\n\nIn the early years, under the influence of [[Abdullah Cevdet]], he wrote articles in [[Ijtihad]] magazine with positivist and materialist thoughts. In particular, he participated in the discussion between Abdullah Cevdet and Celal Nuri Ileri [11]. During the period of Armistice, he generally gave both a westernist and a nationalist appearance. [5] He approached [[Turkish Letter Revolution]], which took place during the time of [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]], anxiously considering that it would cause cultural disconnections between generations, but in the following periods he became one of the complementary of this revolution and participated in language congresses. [12]\n\n=== Relations with Naz\u0131m Hikmet ===\n\n[[File:Nazim Hikmet (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]]\n\nWhen [[N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]] arrived in [[Turkey]] to benefit from the amnesty law, Safa published the poem \"Volcano\", which belongs to Naz\u0131m for the forgiveness of him in [[Cumhuriyet]]. The next day, Cumhuriyet made a statement that the signature under the poem did not reflect its own views and missions. After this announcement, Safa left the newspaper and started writing in the journal [[Resimli Ay]], published by [[Sabiha Sertel]] and [[Zekeriya Sertel]]. [6] Apart from them, N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet, [[Sabahattin Ali]], [[Vala Nureddin|V\u00e2l\u00e2 Nureddin]] and [[Cevat \u015eakir Kabaa\u011fa\u00e7l\u0131]] were among the most well-known authors of this magazine. [13] Peyami Safa and N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet worked together in the journal ''Hareket''in the following periods. The friendship between the two names continued with Peyami Safa's dedication to ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu'', to N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet. [2] N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet, on the other hand, used the following expressions about the novel in Resimli Ay (the Illustrated Moon) by referring to [[Re\u015fat Nuri G\u00fcntekin]]'s [[\u00c7al\u0131ku\u015fu]]:\n\n{{Quote|I have read this last novel of Peyami three times. I can read and read thirty times more ... It is not possible for those who cry to ''\u00c7al\u0131ku\u015fu'' to understand ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu''. It would be sold by ten thousand, one hundred thousand, one million; if they knew how to read and write the self and pure masses of people who heard the anguish, torment and joy with great enthusiasm. [14]}}\n\nSafa has published an article titled ''Var\u0131z Diyen Nesil'' (The Generation who says We Exist) in the first issue of the journal ''Hareket''. When this article reflects the views of young literary writers and the new generation mentioned, this was criticized by Yakup Kadri Karaosmano\u011flu in [[Milliyet]], the famous pencil fight called ''Saman Ekme\u011fi Kavgas\u0131'' (The Fight of Straw Bread) started in the history of Turkish press. [15] Safa was accused of being [[Bolshevik]] for participating in the discussions titled ''Putlar\u0131 Y\u0131k\u0131yoruz''(We Are Destroying the Idols) [16], which started in Resimli Ay, together with N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet and writing articles in the left-wing newspaper [[Tan]] [17]. But he always denied these allegations. [6] The friendship of the two continued after the closing of Resimli Ay. In time, N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet's desire to bring him to [[communism]] and as a result of his efforts to discourage N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet from this ideology, this friendship turned into a great hostility. [18] N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet accused Peyami Safa in his article titled ''Coffee and Casino Intellectuals'' written ,n Tan under the pseudonym Orhan Selim. Peyami Safa also responded to N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet under the series titled ''Biraz Ayd\u0131nl\u0131k'' in the magazine ''Hafta'', which he published with his brother. [19] From this point on, Peyami Safa adopted an anti-communist worldview until the end of his life. [6] In the following process, Peyami Safa's works with the signature of [[Server Bedi]] and [[Cing\u00f6z Recai]] typing became the main subject of the discussions between the two. [20] [21]\n\n=== After ''Resimli Ay'' ===\n=== World War II and afterwards ===\n=== the Democratic  Party period ===\n=== Death ===\n[[File:Peyami Safa's grave.jpg|thumb|The grave of the Safa family in Edirnekap\u0131 Cemetery]]\n\nHe died on June 15, 1961 in Istanbul at the age of 62 after couple of months his son Merve died, as he was serving his time in the military. Peyami Safa was laid to rest at the [[Edirnekap\u0131 Martyr's Cemetery]]. He was the editor-in-chief of the daily ''Son Havadis'' as he died.<ref name=\"b\"/>\n=== Diseases in his family ===\n\n== Literary Life ==\nMost of his novels were created before 1940. In these novels, he stressed on the west-east conflict in the Turkish society during the early years of the [[Turkish Republic]]. His novel ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu'' gained much interest. In 1931, he wrote his only historical novel about ''Attila the Hun''. Besides these novels, he wrote many serial stories and novels in newspapers, among them in ''[[Cumhuriyet]]'' and ''[[Milliyet]]'', under the pseudonym \"Server Bedii\". Some of these are about a [[gentleman thief]] named [[Cing\u00f6z Recai]].<ref name=\"b\"/>\n=== Biography Writing ===\n=== Server Bedi ===\n=== Novels ===\n\n*S\u00f6zde K\u0131zlar (1922, ''So-called Girls'')\t\n*\u015eim\u015fek (1923, ''Lightning'')\t\n*Mah\u015fer (1924, ''Armageddon'')\t\n*Bir Ak\u015famd\u0131 (1924, ''One Evening'')\t\n*S\u00fcng\u00fclerin G\u00f6lgesinde (1924, ''Shadows of the Bayonets'')\t\n*Bir Gen\u00e7 K\u0131z Kalbinin C\u00fcrm\u00fc (1925, ''The Crime of the Young Girl's Heart'')\t\n*Canan (1925,)\t\n*Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu (1930, ''The Ninth External Ward''))\t\n*Fatih-Harbiye (1931)\t\n*Bir Teredd\u00fcd\u00fcn Roman\u0131 (1933, ''The novel of the Hesitation'')\t\n*Matmazel Noraliya'n\u0131n Koltu\u011fu (1949, ''The Armchair of Mme Noraliya'')\t*\n*Yaln\u0131z\u0131z (1951, We are Alone))\t\n*Biz \u0130nsanlar (1959, ''We, Humans'')\n\n=== Diseases in his novels ===\n=== Women in his novels ===\n=== Short stories ===\n\n== Understanding of Art and Literature ==\n=== Art and literary movements ===\n=== Novel and poetry ===\n\n== World of Thought ==\n=== Nationalism ===\n=== Conservatism ===\n=== Thoughts about language ===\n=== East-West Synthesis ===\n=== Thoughts about religion ===\n=== Thoughts about foreigners and foreign developments ===\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Academic studies about Peyami Safa by years.png|thumb|right|Academic studies about Peyami Safa by years in Turkey (1984-2016)]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\nHe wrote 15 novels, excluding those written under pseudonym. He also wrote 17 non-fictions and 9 textbooks mostly about literature.<ref name=\"b\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biyografi.net/kisiayrinti.asp?kisiid=259 |publisher=Biyografi |title=Peyami Safa ( 1899)- (15.06.1961)  |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-01-14 }}</ref>\n\n* \u015eim\u015fek (1923) (Lightning)\n* S\u00f6zde K\u0131zlar (1923) (So-called Girls)\n* Mah\u015fer (1924) (Armageddon)\n* Bir Ak\u015famd\u0131 (1924) (It Was an Evening)\n* S\u00fcng\u00fclerin G\u00f6lgesinde (1924) (In Shadow of Bayonets)\n* Bir Gen\u00e7 K\u0131z Kalbinin C\u00fcrm\u00fc (1925) (The Crime of a Young Girl's Heart) \n* Canan (1925)\n* [[Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu]] (1930) (Ninth External Ward)\n* [[Fatih-Harbiye]] (1931)\n* Atilla (1931)\n* Bir Teredd\u00fcd\u00fcn Roman\u0131 (1933) (The Novel of a Hesitation)\n* [[Matmazel Noraliya'n\u0131n Koltu\u011fu]] (1949) (The Armchair of Mademoiselle Noraliya)\n* [[Yaln\u0131z\u0131z]] (1951) (We Are Alone)\n* Biz \u0130nsanlar (1959) (We People)\n\n=== Play ===\n\n* G\u00fcn Do\u011fuyor (1932) (The Day Is Coming)\n\n=== Other Works ===\n\n* Cumhuriyet Mekteplerine Alfabe (1929) (Alphabet to Republic Schools)\n* Cumhuriyet Mekteplerine K\u0131raat (1929) (Reading to Republican Schools)\n* Yeni Talebe Mektuplar\u0131 (1930) (New Student Letters)\n* B\u00fcy\u00fck Mektup N\u00fcmuneleri (1932) (Great Letter Examples)\n* T\u00fcrk \u0130nk\u0131l\u00e2b\u0131na Bak\u0131\u015flar (1938) (Perspectives on Turkish Revolution)\n* B\u00fcy\u00fck Avrupa Anketi (1938) (Great Europe Survey)\n* Felsef\u00ee Buhran (1939) (Philosophical Crisis)\n* T\u00fcrk Grameri (1941) (Turkish Grammar)\n* Frans\u0131z Grameri (1942) (French Grammar) (It was expanded in 1948 as \"T\u00fcrk\u00e7e \u0130zahl\u0131 Frans\u0131z Grameri\" )\n* Millet ve \u0130nsan (1943) (Nation and Human) (It was expanded in 1961 as \"[[Nationalism|Nasyonalizm]]\")\n* Mahutlar (1959) \n* [[Mysticism|Mistisizm]] (1961) \n* [[Socialism|Sosyalizm]] (1961) \n* Do\u011fu-Bat\u0131 Sentezi (1963) (East-West Synthesis)\n* Objektif Serisi (8 Books) (1970\u20131976) (Objective Series)\n* Hik\u00e2yeler (1980) (Stories)\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n<references/>\n{{Turkish literature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safa, Peyami}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:Writers from Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Turkish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Turkish novelists]]\n[[Category:Turkish journalists]]\n[[Category:Turkish columnists]]\n[[Category:Cumhuriyet people]]\n[[Category:Milliyet people]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Edirnekap\u0131 Martyr's Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Akbaba people]]\n[[Category:20th-century novelists]]\n[[Category:Turkish autobiographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Turkish writer and journalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Expand Turkish|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer  \n| name          = Peyami Safa\n| image         = Peyami Safa is working in Yedig\u00fcn.png\n| image_size    = 250 px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Peyami Safa is working in Yedig\u00fcn Magazine\n| pseudonym     = Server Bedi{{,}}\u00c7\u00f6mez{{,}}Ser\u00e2z\u00e2d{{,}}Safiye Peyman{{,}}Bedia Servet\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1899|4|2}}\n| birth_place   = [[Fatih]], [[Istanbul]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1961|6|15|1899|4|2}} \n| death_place   = [[Kad\u0131k\u00f6y]], Istanbul, Turkey\n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer{{,}}journalist\n| nationality   = Turkish\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     =\n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = 1910\u20131961\n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = [[Cing\u00f6z Recai]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Nebahat Erin\u00e7|1938}}\n| partner       = \n| children      = Merve Safa\n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Peyami Safa''' (April 2, 1899 \u2013 June 15, 1961) was a [[Index of Turkey biography-related articles|Turkish]] journalist, columnist and novelist. He came to the fore in the [[Turkish literature]] of the Republican era with his psychological works such as ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu'' (Ninth External Ward). He reflected his life and his changes to his works. He wrote many novels under the pseudonym ''Server Bedi''. He created the type ''Cing\u00f6z Recai'' inspired by [[Ars\u00e8ne Lupin]] of the French writer [[Maurice Leblanc]]. He also worked as a journalist at various institutions and published several magazines such as K\u00fclt\u00fcr Haftas\u0131 with his brother \u0130lhami Safa.\n\nThe poet [[Tevfik Fikret]] named him when he was born. After he lost his father at a young age, he lived under difficult conditions with his mother and brother. Bone tuberculosis appeared on the right arm. He processed his psychology in those years in his autobiographical novel, Ninth External Ward. He gave his first literary products during his education in [[Vefa High School]]. He worked as a teacher for a short time. The stories he published under the title ''Stories of the Century'' drew attention and received encouraging reactions. He entered pen quarrels with prominent literary writers of the period. He experienced various changes by exhibiting [[Positivism|positivist]], [[materialist]], [[mystical]], [[nationalist]], [[conservative]], [[anti-communist]] and [[corporatist]] attitudes. With his knowledge of [[French language|French]], he closely followed Western culture and innovations. In his early days, he made translations from names such as [[Maupassant]] and [[Rousseau]]. He always chose [[Istanbul]] as the venue for his later works and never gave up the synthesis and analysis of the East and the West. He published articles with critical style in newspapers such as [[Milliyet]]. His good relationships with [[N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]] and [[Necip Faz\u0131l K\u0131sak\u00fcrek]] turned into pen fights over time. At first, he became closer to the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]], then to the [[Democratic Party (Turkey, 1946)|Democratic Party]].\n\nHe continued his literary life, which he started at a young age, until his death. He was mainly [[nationalist]] and [[conservative]]. [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Ministry of National Education]] recommended his two books for secondary school students. His works were also adapted to the cinema and series in various periods.\n\n== Life ==\n=== Early life ===\n[[File:Peyami Safa's childhood photo for a magazine.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A childhood photo of Peyami Safa (1913)]]\nPeyami Safa was born on April 2, 1889 in Gedikpa\u015fa and named after Tevfik Fikret, one of the poets of [[Servet-i F\u00fcn\u00fbn]]. His father is \u0130smail Safa, who was referred to as a \"mother-born poet\" by [[Muallim Naci]] and belonging to a family of [[Trabzon]] origin. Her mother is Server Bedia Han\u0131m. Peyami Safa's father was one of the opponents of [[Abd\u00fclhamid II]] and died in [[Sivas]] while in exile without leaving anything financial to his family. <ref name=\":CB\u00dc\">{{Cite book |last1=Selim |first1=Alt\u0131ntop |last2=R\u0131za|first2=Ba\u011fc\u0131|last3=Can|first3=\u015een| title = Vefat\u0131n\u0131n 50. Y\u0131l\u0131nda Peyami Safa | url = http://en.sbe.cbu.edu.tr/db_images/site_1033/file/peyami_safa_kitabi.pdf |place= Manisa| publisher = Celal Bayar \u00dcniversitesi Sosyal Bilimler Enstit\u00fcs\u00fc | date = 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170202145309/http://en.sbe.cbu.edu.tr/db_images/site_1033/file/peyami_safa_kitabi.pdf | archive-date=2017}}</ref>  Peyami Safa, who lost his father when he was one and a half years old, was brought up by his mother under hard conditions with his brother Ilhami Safa. During his primary education, bone tuberculosis appeared in his right arm. Due to his illness, he could not attend school and found himself among doctors, patients and caregivers at a young age. He influenced the effect of this disease in his work, [[Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu]]. <ref name=\":Bilkent\">{{Cite web| last1 = Aksoy | first1 = S\u00fcreyya Elif |title = Peyami Safa Romanlar\u0131nda Modernle\u015fme ve Mekan | url = http://www.thesis.bilkent.edu.tr/0003885.pdf | publisher = [[Bilkent University]] | date = 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHe started his high school education in [[Vefa High School]] in [[Fatih]] in [[1910]]. During these years, he was a classmate with [[Ekrem Hakk\u0131 Ayverdi]] and [[Elif Naci]]. Also [[Hasan \u00c2li Y\u00fccel]] and [[Yusuf Ziya Orta\u00e7]] were among their high school friends. He gave his first literary discussions and products in those years. He wrote his first story essay ''Piano Teaching'' and his first novel essay ''Eski Dost'' in high school. In addition, the first story book titled ''Don't Take This Book'', which he published during these periods, aroused curiosity and sold out within a few days. <ref>{{cite book|last=G\u00f6ze|first=Ergun|title=Peyami Safa-Naz\u0131m Hikmet Kavgas\u0131|date=1963|location=\u0130stanbul|isbn=|page=42|publisher=Ya\u011fmur Yay\u0131nlar\u0131}}</ref>  He could not continue his high school education due to his illness and his family's livelihood problems.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ayvazo\u011flu|first=Be\u015fir|title=Peyami Hayat\u0131 Sanat\u0131 Felsefesi Dram\u0131|date=1998|location=\u0130stanbul|isbn=|page=37\u201354|publisher=[[\u00d6t\u00fcken Ne\u015friyat]]}}</ref> He developed the knowledge of [[French language|French]] by memorizing [[Petit Larousse]], a gift from his father's close friends, [[Abdullah Cevdet]], and began to be interested in [[medicine]], [[psychology]] and [[philosophy]] books besides literary works. Due to his interest in the [[theater]] in the future, he took the [[Dar\u00fclbedayi|D\u00e2r\u00fclbedayi]] exams but could not continue despite his success. During the times of [[the First World War]], he started working in the Post Office to help his mother. <ref name=\":A\u00dc\">{{Cite web| author = Ya\u015far \u00d6zkanda\u015f | title = Peyami Safa'n\u0131n D\u00fc\u015f\u00fcnceleri Ekseninde T\u00fcrk Modernle\u015fmesinin \u0130ncelenmesi | url = https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1Wt13HgwVD_UzZuUVA4bmFRZVk | publisher = [[Ankara University]] | date = 2016}}</ref> Later, he was appointed as a teacher to the Rehber-i \u0130ttihad School in Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i (1917) and worked for a while in the [[D\u00fcyun-u Umumiye|D\u00fcy\u00fbn-\u0131 Um\u00fbmiye Administration]] (1918).<ref name=\":TDV\u0130A\">{{cite encyclopedia |author-link=[[Be\u015fir Ayvazo\u011flu]] |encyclopedia= TDV \u0130sl\u00e2m Ansiklopedisi |title=Safa, Peyami |url= |language= Turkish | date=2008 |publisher= Turkey Diyanet Foundation |volume=35 |location= \u0130stanbul |isbn=978-975-389-457-9 |oclc= |doi= |page=437\u2013440 |ref= }}</ref>\n\n=== Armistice and the Republican Era ===\n{{Cquote|These stories then gained a great success among the public, which still amazed me. The young literature of that time encouraged me fervently, asking me to sign my stories. [[Yakup Kadri Karaosmano\u011flu|Yakup Kadri]] says, \"You brought us a style,\" [[Yahya Kemal]] said, \"Peyami is the most beautiful work of Ismail Safa\". [7]|source= Peyami Safa, after his stories, which he published under the title ''Y\u00fczy\u0131l\u0131n Hik\u00e2yeleri'' (\"Stories of the Century\"), attracted attention.|float=right |width=30%}}\nPeyami Safa, who left his teaching position at the Rehber-i \u0130ttihad School during the armistice period in [[1918]], started publishing the newspaper Twentieth Century (Yirminci Y\u00fczy\u0131l) with his brother. In this newspaper, he drew attention with the stories he published under the heading \"Stories of the Century\". [8] He also made his first pen fight against [[Cenap \u015eahabettin]]'s adaptation play (1919). When he received a degree in the story contest organized by Alemdar newspaper, he was encouraged to write by the leading writers of the period. After ''Yirminci Y\u00fczy\u0131l'' was closed, they lasted his profession in journalism in places such as [[Terc\u00fcman-\u0131 Hakikat]] and [[Tasvir-i Efkar|Tasvir-i Efk\u00e2r]] (1922) after the declaration of the Republic. In addition, he published his first novel, ''[[S\u00f6zde K\u0131zlar]]'' (So-called Girls), for his livelihood. By [[1924]], He published his several works including ''Mah\u015fer'', ''Bir Gece'' (One Evening), ''S\u00fcng\u00fclerin G\u00f6lgesinde'' (In the Shadow of the Bayonets) and ''Istanbul Hikayeleri'' (the Stories of Istanbul). [9] In [[1925]], he published a short-lived newspaper called B\u00fcy\u00fck Yol with [[Halil L\u00fctf\u00fc D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc]]. Also in these years, he wrote in [[Cumhuriyet]] newspaper with the signature of \"Server Bedi\" and \"Peyami Safa\". He went on his relationship with the newspaper as a columnist and literature manager (1928-1940). His article titled \"New Literary Circles\" published in Hilal-i Ahmer magazine led to a pencil fight with [[Ahmet Ha\u015fim]] (1928). [10]\n\nIn the early years, under the influence of [[Abdullah Cevdet]], he wrote articles in [[Ijtihad]] magazine with positivist and materialist thoughts. In particular, he participated in the discussion between Abdullah Cevdet and Celal Nuri Ileri [11]. During the period of Armistice, he generally gave both a westernist and a nationalist appearance. [5] He approached [[Turkish Letter Revolution]], which took place during the time of [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]], anxiously considering that it would cause cultural disconnections between generations, but in the following periods he became one of the complementary of this revolution and participated in language congresses. [12]\n\n=== Relations with Naz\u0131m Hikmet ===\n\n[[File:Nazim Hikmet (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]]\n\nWhen [[N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]] arrived in [[Turkey]] to benefit from the amnesty law, Safa published the poem \"Volcano\", which belongs to Naz\u0131m for the forgiveness of him in [[Cumhuriyet]]. The next day, Cumhuriyet made a statement that the signature under the poem did not reflect its own views and missions. After this announcement, Safa left the newspaper and started writing in the journal [[Resimli Ay]], published by [[Sabiha Sertel]] and [[Zekeriya Sertel]]. [6] Apart from them, N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet, [[Sabahattin Ali]], [[Vala Nureddin|V\u00e2l\u00e2 Nureddin]] and [[Cevat \u015eakir Kabaa\u011fa\u00e7l\u0131]] were among the most well-known authors of this magazine. [13] Peyami Safa and N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet worked together in the journal ''Hareket''in the following periods. The friendship between the two names continued with Peyami Safa's dedication to ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu'', to N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet. [2] N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet, on the other hand, used the following expressions about the novel in Resimli Ay (the Illustrated Moon) by referring to [[Re\u015fat Nuri G\u00fcntekin]]'s [[\u00c7al\u0131ku\u015fu]]:\n\n{{Quote|I have read this last novel of Peyami three times. I can read and read thirty times more ... It is not possible for those who cry to ''\u00c7al\u0131ku\u015fu'' to understand ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu''. It would be sold by ten thousand, one hundred thousand, one million; if they knew how to read and write the self and pure masses of people who heard the anguish, torment and joy with great enthusiasm. [14]}}\n\nSafa has published an article titled ''Var\u0131z Diyen Nesil'' (The Generation who says We Exist) in the first issue of the journal ''Hareket''. When this article reflects the views of young literary writers and the new generation mentioned, this was criticized by Yakup Kadri Karaosmano\u011flu in [[Milliyet]], the famous pencil fight called ''Saman Ekme\u011fi Kavgas\u0131'' (The Fight of Straw Bread) started in the history of Turkish press. [15] Safa was accused of being [[Bolshevik]] for participating in the discussions titled ''Putlar\u0131 Y\u0131k\u0131yoruz''(We Are Destroying the Idols) [16], which started in Resimli Ay, together with N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet and writing articles in the left-wing newspaper [[Tan]] [17]. But he always denied these allegations. [6] The friendship of the two continued after the closing of Resimli Ay. In time, N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet's desire to bring him to [[communism]] and as a result of his efforts to discourage N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet from this ideology, this friendship turned into a great hostility. [18] N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet accused Peyami Safa in his article titled ''Coffee and Casino Intellectuals'' written ,n Tan under the pseudonym Orhan Selim. Peyami Safa also responded to N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet under the series titled ''Biraz Ayd\u0131nl\u0131k'' in the magazine ''Hafta'', which he published with his brother. [19] From this point on, Peyami Safa adopted an anti-communist worldview until the end of his life. [6] In the following process, Peyami Safa's works with the signature of [[Server Bedi]] and [[Cing\u00f6z Recai]] typing became the main subject of the discussions between the two. [20] [21]\n\n=== After ''Resimli Ay'' ===\n=== World War II and afterwards ===\n=== the Democratic  Party period ===\n=== Death ===\n[[File:Peyami Safa's grave.jpg|thumb|The grave of the Safa family in Edirnekap\u0131 Cemetery]]\n\nHe died on June 15, 1961 in Istanbul at the age of 62 after couple of months his son Merve died, as he was serving his time in the military. Peyami Safa was laid to rest at the [[Edirnekap\u0131 Martyr's Cemetery]]. He was the editor-in-chief of the daily ''Son Havadis'' as he died.<ref name=\"b\"/>\n=== Diseases in his family ===\n\n== Literary Life ==\nMost of his novels were created before 1940. In these novels, he stressed on the west-east conflict in the Turkish society during the early years of the [[Turkish Republic]]. His novel ''Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu'' gained much interest. In 1931, he wrote his only historical novel about ''Attila the Hun''. Besides these novels, he wrote many serial stories and novels in newspapers, among them in ''[[Cumhuriyet]]'' and ''[[Milliyet]]'', under the pseudonym \"Server Bedii\". Some of these are about a [[gentleman thief]] named [[Cing\u00f6z Recai]].<ref name=\"b\"/>\n=== Biography Writing ===\n=== Server Bedi ===\n=== Novels ===\n\nS\u00f6zde K\u0131zlar (1922, ''So-called Girls'')\t\n\u015eim\u015fek (1923, ''Lightning'')\t\nMah\u015fer (1924, ''Armageddon'')\t\nBir Ak\u015famd\u0131 (1924, ''One Evening'')\t\nS\u00fcng\u00fclerin G\u00f6lgesinde (1924, ''Shadows of the Bayonets'')\t\nBir Gen\u00e7 K\u0131z Kalbinin C\u00fcrm\u00fc (1925, ''The Crime of the Young Girl's Heart'')\t\nC\u00e2n\u00e2n (1925,)\t\nDokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu (1930, ''The Ninth External Ward''))\t\nFatih-Harbiye (1931)\t\nBir Teredd\u00fcd\u00fcn Roman\u0131 (1933, ''The novel of the Hesitation'')\t\nMatmazel Noraliya'n\u0131n Koltu\u011fu (1949, ''The Armchair of Mme Noraliya'')\t\nYaln\u0131z\u0131z (1951, We are Alone))\t\nBiz \u0130nsanlar (1959, ''We, Humans'')\n\n=== Diseases in his novels ===\n=== Women in his novels ===\n=== Short stories ===\n\n== Understanding of Art and Literature ==\n=== Art and literary movements ===\n=== Novel and poetry ===\n\n== World of Thought ==\n=== Nationalism ===\n=== Conservatism ===\n=== Thoughts about language ===\n=== East-West Synthesis ===\n=== Thoughts about religion ===\n=== Thoughts about foreigners and foreign developments ===\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Academic studies about Peyami Safa by years.png|thumb|right|Academic studies about Peyami Safa by years in Turkey (1984-2016)]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\nHe wrote 15 novels, excluding those written under pseudonym. He also wrote 17 non-fictions and 9 textbooks mostly about literature.<ref name=\"b\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biyografi.net/kisiayrinti.asp?kisiid=259 |publisher=Biyografi |title=Peyami Safa ( 1899)- (15.06.1961)  |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-01-14 }}</ref>\n\n* \u015eim\u015fek (1923) (Lightning)\n* S\u00f6zde K\u0131zlar (1923) (So-called Girls)\n* Mah\u015fer (1924) (Armageddon)\n* Bir Ak\u015famd\u0131 (1924) (It Was an Evening)\n* S\u00fcng\u00fclerin G\u00f6lgesinde (1924) (In Shadow of Bayonets)\n* Bir Gen\u00e7 K\u0131z Kalbinin C\u00fcrm\u00fc (1925) (The Crime of a Young Girl's Heart) \n* Canan (1925)\n* [[Dokuzuncu Hariciye Ko\u011fu\u015fu]] (1930) (Ninth External Ward)\n* [[Fatih-Harbiye]] (1931)\n* Atilla (1931)\n* Bir Teredd\u00fcd\u00fcn Roman\u0131 (1933) (The Novel of a Hesitation)\n* [[Matmazel Noraliya'n\u0131n Koltu\u011fu]] (1949) (The Armchair of Mademoiselle Noraliya)\n* [[Yaln\u0131z\u0131z]] (1951) (We Are Alone)\n* Biz \u0130nsanlar (1959) (We People)\n\n=== Play ===\n\n* G\u00fcn Do\u011fuyor (1932) (The Day Is Coming)\n\n=== Other Works ===\n\n* Cumhuriyet Mekteplerine Alfabe (1929) (Alphabet to Republic Schools)\n* Cumhuriyet Mekteplerine K\u0131raat (1929) (Reading to Republican Schools)\n* Yeni Talebe Mektuplar\u0131 (1930) (New Student Letters)\n* B\u00fcy\u00fck Mektup N\u00fcmuneleri (1932) (Great Letter Examples)\n* T\u00fcrk \u0130nk\u0131l\u00e2b\u0131na Bak\u0131\u015flar (1938) (Perspectives on Turkish Revolution)\n* B\u00fcy\u00fck Avrupa Anketi (1938) (Great Europe Survey)\n* Felsef\u00ee Buhran (1939) (Philosophical Crisis)\n* T\u00fcrk Grameri (1941) (Turkish Grammar)\n* Frans\u0131z Grameri (1942) (French Grammar) (It was expanded in 1948 as \"T\u00fcrk\u00e7e \u0130zahl\u0131 Frans\u0131z Grameri\" )\n* Millet ve \u0130nsan (1943) (Nation and Human) (It was expanded in 1961 as \"[[Nationalism|Nasyonalizm]]\")\n* Mahutlar (1959) \n* [[Mysticism|Mistisizm]] (1961) \n* [[Socialism|Sosyalizm]] (1961) \n* Do\u011fu-Bat\u0131 Sentezi (1963) (East-West Synthesis)\n* Objektif Serisi (8 Books) (1970\u20131976) (Objective Series)\n* Hik\u00e2yeler (1980) (Stories)\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n<references/>\n{{Turkish literature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safa, Peyami}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:Writers from Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Turkish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Turkish novelists]]\n[[Category:Turkish journalists]]\n[[Category:Turkish columnists]]\n[[Category:Cumhuriyet people]]\n[[Category:Milliyet people]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Edirnekap\u0131 Martyr's Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Akbaba people]]\n[[Category:20th-century novelists]]\n[[Category:Turkish autobiographers]]\n", "name_user": "Nedim Ardo\u011fa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNovels", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.