er)|Martin Power]]\n|- \n| Petrolon Slick 50 Racing\n| Mazda RX-7\n| 50\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter McLeod]]\n|-\n| David Grose\n| [[Mazda RX-7]]\n| 52\n| [[David Grose (racing driver)|David Grose]]\n|-\n| Swiss Motors\n| Mazda RX-7\n| 53\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ernie Carniello]]\n|-\n| [[Barry Seton]]\n| Ford Capri Mk.III\n| 55\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Glenn Seton]]\n|- \n| Jim Myhill\n| Mazda RX-7\n| 57\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Jim Myhill]]\n|-\n| Lawrie Nelson\n| Ford Capri Mk.III\n| 59\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lawrie Nelson]] \n|- \n| Les Ski Racing\n| [[Isuzu Gemini]]\n| 61\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Les Szreniawski\n|-\n| Denis Horley \n| Isuzu Gemini\n| 62\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Denis Horley]] <ref name=Horley>Australian Motor Racing Year 1984/85, page 201</ref>\n|-  \n| Peter Brierley\n| Holden VH Commodore SS\n| 62\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter Brierley]]\n|-  \n| John White\n| [[Isuzu Gemini]]\n| 65\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[John White (racing driver)|John White]]\n|-  \n| Ian Burrell\n| [[Mitsubishi Mirage|Mitsubishi Colt]]\n| 66\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ian Burrell (racing driver)|Ian Burrell]]\n|- \n| Fred Geissler\n| Holden VH Commodore\n| 66\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Fred Geissler]]\n|-\n| Alexandra Surplice\n| [[Toyota Corolla Levin]]\n| 67\n| [[Alexandra Surplice]]\n|-\n| Lyndon Arnel\n| Ford Escort Mk.II\n| 68\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lyndon Arnel]] \n|- \n| Don Smith\n| Ford Capri Mk.III\n| 69\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Don Smith (racing driver)|Don Smith]]\n|- \n| Colin Campbell\n| Holden VH Commodore\n| 70\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Colin Campbell (racing driver)|Colin Campbell]]\n|-\n| [[Bob Holden Motors]]\n| [[Toyota Celica]]\n| 73\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Bob Holden (racing driver)|Bob Holden]]\n|-\n| Garry McGrath\n| Ford Escort Mk.II\n| 77\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Garry McGrath]]\n|-\n| Clynton Arentz\n| Ford Escort Mk.II\n| 79\n| [[Clynton Arentz]]\n|-\n| Ken Harrison\n| Ford Escort Mk.II\n| 80\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Harrison (racing driver)|Ken Harrison]]\n|- \n| Russell Worthington\n| [[Mazda 626]]\n| 100\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Worthington]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Race Calendar==\nThe 1984 [[Australian Touring Car Championship]] was contested over a seven-round series with one race per round.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|-\n!Rd.\n!Race Title\n!Circuit\n!City / State\n!Date\n!Winner\n!Team\n!Report\n|-\n! 1\n| ''[[Sandown ATCC round|Sandown]]''\n| [[Sandown International Raceway]]\n| [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| 18 February\n| [[Peter Brock]]\n| [[Marlboro Holden Dealer Team]]\n| <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uviyMbY4BUA 1984 ATCC Rd.1]</ref>\n|-\n! 2\n| ''[[Symmons Plains ATCC round|Symmons Plains]]''\n| [[Symmons Plains Raceway]]\n| [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]], [[Tasmania]]\n| 11 March\n| Peter Brock\n| Marlboro Holden Dealer Team\n|\n|-\n! 3\n| ''[[Wanneroo ATCC round|Wanneroo]]''\n| [[Barbagallo Raceway|Wanneroo Park Raceway]] <ref>[http://www.terrywalkersplace.com/Programs/1984-april.jpg Official Programme, Wanneroo Park Raceway, Sunday 1 April 1984] Retrieved from www.terrywalkersplace.com on 7 July 2009</ref>\n| [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], [[Western Australia]]\n| 1 April\n| [[Allan Moffat]]\n| [[Allan Moffat Racing|Peter Stuyvesant International Racing]]\n|\n|-\n! 4\n| ''[[Surfers Paradise ATCC round|Surfers Paradise]]''\n| [[Surfers Paradise International Raceway]]\n| [[Surfers Paradise]], [[Queensland]]\n| 13 May\n| [[Dick Johnson (racing driver)|Dick Johnson]]\n| [[Dick Johnson Racing|Palmer Tube Mills]]\n| <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qptgnp-cnzg 1984 ATCC Rd.4]</ref>\n|-\n! 5\n| [[Oran Park ATCC round|The Castrol Flying Fifty]]<ref>{{cite web |title=1984 ATCC |url=http://www.progcovers.com/motor/atcc1984.html |website=The Programme Covers Project |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Oran Park Raceway]]\n| [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| 27 May\n| [[Bob Morris (motor racing)|Bob Morris]]\n| Barry Jones\n| <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VM9o90KwjGg 1984 ATCC Rd.5]</ref>\n|-\n! 6\n| ''[[Lakeside ATCC round|Lakeside]]''\n| [[Lakeside International Raceway]]\n| [[Brisbane, Queensland|Brisbane]], Queensland\n| 17 June\n| [[George Fury]]\n| [[Gibson Motor Sport|Nissan Motor Co]]\n|\n|-\n! 7\n| [[Adelaide ATCC round|Motorcraft 100]]<ref>Official Programme, Motorcraft 100, Adelaide International Raceway, Sunday 1 July 1984</ref>\n| [[Adelaide International Raceway]]\n| [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\n| 1 July\n| [[Allan Grice]]\n| [[Roadways Racing]]\n| <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YNs7PDrstoQ 1984 ATCC Rd.7]</ref>\n|}\n\n==Points system==\nCars competed in two engine displacement classes, \"up to and including 3000cc\" and \"3001-6000cc\".<ref name=CAMS1984/>\n\nPoints were awarded for the first twenty outright places in each round using a two tier system as shown in the following table.<ref name=CAMS1984/>\n\n3001-6000cc consisted of [[BMW E24|BMW 635 CSi]], [[Chevrolet Camaro (second generation)#1979|Chevrolet Camaro Z28]], [[Ford XD Falcon]], [[Ford XE Falcon]], [[Holden VH Commodore]], [[Mazda RX-7]] and [[Datsun Bluebird 910|Nissan Bluebird Turbo]].\n\nUp to and including 3000cc consisted of [[Ford Capri Mk.III]], [[Ford Escort (Europe)|Ford Escort Mk.II]], [[Isuzu Gemini#1974|Isuzu Gemini]], [[Mazda 323]], [[Mazda 626]], [[Mitsubishi Mirage|Mitsubishi Colt]], [[Toyota Celica]] and [[Triumph Dolomite Sprint]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" <hiddentext>generated with [[:de:Wikipedia:Helferlein/VBA-Macro for EXCEL tableconversion]] V1.7<\\hiddentext>\n|-  align=\"center\"\n|style=\"font-weight:bold\" height=\"14\" | Outright position <ref name=CAMS1984/>\n| width=\"24\" | 1st\n| width=\"24\" | 2nd\n| width=\"24\" | 3rd\n| width=\"24\" | 4th\n| width=\"24\" | 5th\n| width=\"24\" | 6th\n| width=\"24\" | 7th\n| width=\"24\" | 8th\n| width=\"24\" | 9th\n| width=\"24\" | 10th\n| width=\"24\" | 11th\n| width=\"24\" | 12th\n| width=\"24\" | 13th\n| width=\"24\" | 14th\n| width=\"24\" | 15th\n| width=\"24\" | 1