dia.org/wiki/1981%E2%80%9382_St._Francis_Terriers_men%27s_basketball_team"}
{"title_page": "HIT 107", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{About|a regional radio station in Australia|the national radio station in [[South Africa]]|SAfm}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n|name               = hit107\n|image              = File:Hit107_adelaide.jpg\n|city               = \n|area               = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\n|branding           = Shit107\n|slogan             =''More Music, More Variety''\n|frequency          = 107.1 MHz FM (1989\u2013present)\n|translator         = \n|repeater           = \n|airdate            = {{start date|1980|09|12|df=y}}\n|share              = \n|share as of        = \n|share source       = \n|format             = Adult CHR\n|language           = [[English language|English]]\n|power              = \n|erp                = \n|haat               = \n|class              = \n|facility_id        = \n|coordinates        = \n|callsign_meaning   = \n|former_callsigns   = \n|former_frequencies = 107.5 MHz FM (1980\u20131989)\n|affiliations       = [[Hit Network]]\n|owner              = [[Southern Cross Austereo]]\n|licensee           = \n|sister_stations    = [[5MMM]]\n|website  = {{official website|http://www.hit107.com.au/}}\n}}\n'''hit107''' (call sign: '''5SSA''') is a commercial [[FM radio]] station broadcasting in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia, on a frequency of 107.1 [[MHz]], and is part of [[Southern Cross Austereo]]'s [[Today's Hit Network|Hit Network]].\n\n==History==\nThe station commenced broadcasting in 1980, on the frequency of 107.5&nbsp;MHz, with a call sign of 5SSA and an original on-air branding of \"Triple SA-FM\" which was very short-lived and soon replaced by \"Double SA-FM\". It was the first commercial radio station to broadcast on the FM band in Adelaide started by Paul Thompson of the Austereo Network. The first song played on air was \"Sultans of Swing\" by Dire Straits. Initially, SA-FM was somewhat of a fringe operation, hampered largely by the fact that many houses, and more importantly most contemporary cars, did not have the ability to receive FM radio broadcasts.\n\nLater, it changed its name to \"SAFM\", and altered its frequency slightly to 107.1&nbsp;MHz. A second frequency, 91.1&nbsp;MHz, was added as what was the first of many repeater frequencies in Adelaide, required due to Adelaide's sometimes problematic television and radio reception idiosyncrasies. The frequency was later changed to 90.3&nbsp;MHz and it continues to operate on that frequency.\n\nPrior to the commercial introduction of the Compact Disc audio format to the Australian market, SAFM obtained one of the first Sony CD consumer players, which was used on-air for demonstrating this new format to the public.\n\nSAFM was also the first station in the world to have \"Black Thunder\" promotional vehicles.\n\nBetween 1984 until 1993 it was the highest rating station in Adelaide and achieving its best survey results in the late '80s, spearheaded by the \"Morning Zoo\" breakfast show.  SAFM became number one again in 1999, holding that position until 2005, when it dropped back to third, behind the talk station [[FIVEaa]] and the music station [[Mix 102.3]].\n\nFrom its inception SAFM was an adult rock-based format, before switching to CHR in March 1996.  Then in November 2003, SAFM changed from CHR to an adult contemporary format, but both SAFM and [[Triple M Adelaide]] reverted to their original formats in December 2004.\n\nOn Monday 13 October 2014, it was announced that SAFM would relaunch as Hit 107 on Monday 20 October 2014 due to flagging ratings. Amos Gill and Daniela Pola were also announced as the new breakfast team.<ref>http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/5630-hit-107-adelaide-revealed.html</ref> On Monday 20 October 2014, Hit 107 was planning to sign on at 8:00 AM Adelaide Time. The final song before the rebrand was [[NSYNC]]'s, \"[[Bye Bye Bye]]\". The first song following the rebrand was \"Cosby Sweater\" by [[Hilltop Hoods]] and the first non-Australian song was \"[[Blame (Calvin Harris song)|Blame]]\" by [[Calvin Harris]] feat. [[John Newman (singer)|John Newman]].\n\nLocal Television personalities Rebecca Morse & Andrew Costello currently present the Hit 107 Breakfast Show - Bec & Cosi, from 6.00am to 9.00am weekdays.\n\nCurrent Morning announcer is English Chris & Afternoon announcer is Nicole Mitchell.\n\nThe Hit 107 is local weekdays between 6.00am to 3.00pm, with all other programming networked from Fox FM Melbourne & 2Day FM Sydney.\n\n==Digital radio==\nhit107 is simulcast on [[Digital radio in Australia|Digital Radio]] in Adelaide.\n\n==Where To Listen==\n\n* [https://www.radio.net/s/hit107ad radio.net]\n* [https://streema.com/radios/SAFM_2 Streema]\n* [https://tunein.com/radio/hit107-1071-s7026/ TuneIn]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hamish & Andy (radio show)|Hamish & Andy]]\n*[[List of radio stations in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hit107.com.au Official website]\n\n{{Austereo Radio Network}}\n{{Adelaide FM}}\n\n{{coord|34.927135|S| 138.596781|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Contemporary hit radio stations in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{About|a regional radio station in Australia|the national radio station in [[South Africa]]|SAfm}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n|name               = hit107\n|image              = File:Hit107_adelaide.jpg\n|city               = \n|area               = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\n|branding           = hit107\n|slogan             =''More Music, More Variety''\n|frequency          = 107.1 MHz FM (1989\u2013present)\n|translator         = \n|repeater           = \n|airdate            = {{start date|1980|09|12|df=y}}\n|share              = \n|share as of        = \n|share source       = \n|format             = Adult CHR\n|language           = [[English language|English]]\n|power              = \n|erp                = \n|haat               = \n|class              = \n|facility_id        = \n|coordinates        = \n|callsign_meaning   = \n|former_callsigns   = \n|former_frequencies = 107.5 MHz FM (1980\u20131989)\n|affiliations       = [[Hit Network]]\n|owner              = [[Southern Cross Austereo]]\n|licensee           = \n|sister_stations    = [[5MMM]]\n|website  = {{official website|http://www.hit107.com.au/}}\n}}\n'''hit107''' (call sign: '''5SSA''') is a commercial [[FM radio]] station broadcasting in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia, on a frequency of 107.1 [[MHz]], and is part of [[Southern Cross Austereo]]'s [[Today's Hit Network|Hit Network]].\n\n==History==\nThe station commenced broadcasting in 1980, on the frequency of 107.5&nbsp;MHz, with a call sign of 5SSA and an original on-air branding of \"Triple SA-FM\" which was very short-lived and soon replaced by \"Double SA-FM\". It was the first commercial radio station to broadcast on the FM band in Adelaide started by Paul Thompson of the Austereo Network. The first song played on air was \"Sultans of Swing\" by Dire Straits. Initially, SA-FM was somewhat of a fringe operation, hampered largely by the fact that many houses, and more importantly most contemporary cars, did not have the ability to receive FM radio broadcasts.\n\nLater, it changed its name to \"SAFM\", and altered its frequency slightly to 107.1&nbsp;MHz. A second frequency, 91.1&nbsp;MHz, was added as what was the first of many repeater frequencies in Adelaide, required due to Adelaide's sometimes problematic television and radio reception idiosyncrasies. The frequency was later changed to 90.3&nbsp;MHz and it continues to operate on that frequency.\n\nPrior to the commercial introduction of the Compact Disc audio format to the Australian market, SAFM obtained one of the first Sony CD consumer players, which was used on-air for demonstrating this new format to the public.\n\nSAFM was also the first station in the world to have \"Black Thunder\" promotional vehicles.\n\nBetween 1984 until 1993 it was the highest rating station in Adelaide and achieving its best survey results in the late '80s, spearheaded by the \"Morning Zoo\" breakfast show.  SAFM became number one again in 1999, holding that position until 2005, when it dropped back to third, behind the talk station [[FIVEaa]] and the music station [[Mix 102.3]].\n\nFrom its inception SAFM was an adult rock-based format, before switching to CHR in March 1996.  Then in November 2003, SAFM changed from CHR to an adult contemporary format, but both SAFM and [[Triple M Adelaide]] reverted to their original formats in December 2004.\n\nOn Monday 13 October 2014, it was announced that SAFM would relaunch as Hit 107 on Monday 20 October 2014 due to flagging ratings. Amos Gill and Daniela Pola were also announced as the new breakfast team.<ref>http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/5630-hit-107-adelaide-revealed.html</ref> On Monday 20 October 2014, Hit 107 was planning to sign on at 8:00 AM Adelaide Time. The final song before the rebrand was [[NSYNC]]'s, \"[[Bye Bye Bye]]\". The first song following the rebrand was \"Cosby Sweater\" by [[Hilltop Hoods]] and the first non-Australian song was \"[[Blame (Calvin Harris song)|Blame]]\" by [[Calvin Harris]] feat. [[John Newman (singer)|John Newman]].\n\nLocal Television personalities Rebecca Morse & Andrew Costello currently present the Hit 107 Breakfast Show - Bec & Cosi, from 6.00am to 9.00am weekdays.\n\nCurrent Morning announcer is English Chris & Afternoon announcer is Nicole Mitchell.\n\nThe Hit 107 is local weekdays between 6.00am to 3.00pm, with all other programming networked from Fox FM Melbourne & 2Day FM Sydney.\n\n==Digital radio==\nhit107 is simulcast on [[Digital radio in Australia|Digital Radio]] in Adelaide.\n\n==Where To Listen==\n\n* [https://www.radio.net/s/hit107ad radio.net]\n* [https://streema.com/radios/SAFM_2 Streema]\n* [https://tunein.com/radio/hit107-1071-s7026/ TuneIn]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hamish & Andy (radio show)|Hamish & Andy]]\n*[[List of radio stations in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hit107.com.au Official website]\n\n{{Austereo Radio Network}}\n{{Adelaide FM}}\n\n{{coord|34.927135|S| 138.596781|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Contemporary hit radio stations in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8004:1381:97dc:d9de:c1e:ceea:dede", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIT_107"}
{"title_page": "KMPC", "text_new": "{{short description|Korean&ndash;language radio station in Los Angeles}}\n{{For|the Los Angeles station formerly known as KMPC at 710 kHz|KSPN (AM)}}\n<!-- RK was launched in February 1989 on KZAN 1300 AM -->\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = KMPC\n| image            = File:KMPC radiokorea logo.jpg\n| city             = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| area             = [[Greater Los Angeles area|Greater Los Angeles]]\n| branding         = ''Radio Korea''\n| slogan           = \n| frequency        = 1540 [[Kilohertz|kHz]]\n| repeater         = \n| airdate          = September 22, [[1952 in radio|1952]]<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/Section-B-Radio-Broadcasting-Yearbook-1971-;11.pdf 1971 Broadcasting Yearbook]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1971. p. B-;22. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref>\n| format           = [[Korean language|Korean programming]]\n| power            = 50,000 [[watt]]s (day)<br>37,000 watts (night)\n| class            = B\n| facility_id      = 61647\n| coordinates      = {{coord|34|4|43|N|118|11|5|W|region:US-CA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| callsign_meaning = K '''M'''ultilingual '''P'''rogramming '''C'''orporation\n| former_callsigns = KPOL (1952&ndash;1979)<br>KZLA (1979&ndash;1984)<br>KSKQ (1984&ndash;1992)<br>KXED (1992&ndash;1996)<br>KXMG (1996&ndash;1997)<br>KCTD (1997&ndash;2000)\n| affiliations     = \n| owner            = P&Y Broadcasting Corporation\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  = \n| webcast          = \n| website          = [http://www.radiokorea.com/ radiokorea.com]\n}}\n'''KMPC''' (1540 [[Hertz|kHz]], \"Radio Korea\", \ub77c\ub514\uc624\ucf54\ub9ac\uc544) is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[AM radio|AM]] [[radio station]] in [[Los Angeles, California]].  It is owned by P&Y Broadcasting Corporation.  Radio Korea is a division of the Radio Korea Media Group.  The station airs Korean&ndash;language programming, a blend of talk, news, information, and music for the largest [[Korean&ndash;American]] community in the [[United States]], and the largest [[Koreans|Korean]] community outside Korea.  KMPC is one of four radio stations in the greater [[Los Angeles]] area that broadcast entirely in Korean.  The others are 1190 [[KGBN]] [[Anaheim]], 1230 [[KYPA]] Los Angeles and 1650 [[KFOX (AM)|KFOX]] [[Torrance, California|Torrance]].\n\nKMPC broadcasts at 50,000 [[watt]]s by day, the highest power permitted for commercial AM stations.  At night, to reduce interference to other stations on [[AM 1540]], KMPC drops its power to 37,000 watts.  It uses a [[directional antenna]] at all times.  The [[transmitter]] is off Carter Drive in the [[El Sereno, Los Angeles|El Sereno]] district of Los Angeles.<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/finder?sr=Y&s=C&call=Kmpc&nav= Radio-Locator.com/KMPC]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===KPOL===\nOn September 22, 1952, the station [[sign-on|signed on]] with the [[call sign]] '''KPOL'''.<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\" /> It ran 5,000 watts and was originally a [[daytimer]], required to be off the air at sunset.  It was owned by Coast Radio Broadcasting Corporation.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" />  In 1958, it added an FM station at 93.9 MHz, KPOL-FM (now [[KLLI (FM)|KLLI]]).  Then in 1965, it put a television station on the air, Channel 22 KPOL-TV (now [[KWHY-TV]]).\n\nKPOL 1540 went on the air 10 minutes after receiving [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) approval.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31511041/kttv_telecasts_eisenhower_talk_tonight/ |title=KTTV Telecasts Eisenhower Talk Tonight; NBC, CBS Race for TV City Opening Honors |last=Ames |first=Walter |date=1952-09-25 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2019-05-13 |language=en}}</ref> The following year, its power was increased to 10,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" /> Full time operations were added in 1958, with a power of 10,000 watts at night using a directional [[antenna array]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" /> Daytime power was increased to 50,000 watts in 1961.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" />\n\nIn its early years, KPOL aired several [[polka music]] programs.<ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Life/50s/Radio-TV-Life-1953-01-09.pdf TV-Radio Life]''. January 10-16, 1953. Retrieved April 29, 2019</ref> That gave the station its call letters.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31510903/new_radio_station_goes_on_air_today/ |title=New Radio Station Goes on Air Today; KPOL to Transmit Over Frequency of 1540 Kilocycles |date=1952-09-15 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2019-05-13 |language=en}}</ref> [[Tom Kennedy (television host)|Tom Kennedy]], later a popular TV [[game show]] host, was a polka DJ on the station during this era.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Baber|first1=David|title=Television Game Show Hosts: Biographies of 32 Stars|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-1-4766-0480-0|page=133|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VbrwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA133#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 29, 2019|date=2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, KPOL advertised on a billboard at Los Angeles's [[Wrigley Field (Los Angeles)|Wrigley Field]], which can be seen in the [[television series]] ''[[Home Run Derby (TV series)|Home Run Derby]]''.\n\nIn 1966, KPOL-AM-FM were sold to [[Capital Cities/ABC Inc.|Capital Cities Broadcasting]] for $7.8 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1966/1966-07-25-BC.pdf KPOL buy brings Capital up to limit]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. July 25, 1966. p. 58. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"HistoryCards\" />\n\nFor many years, KPOL aired an [[easy listening]]/[[beautiful music]] format on both AM and FM.<ref>Zhito, Lee. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1961/Billboard%201961-02-27.pdf LP Programming]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. February 27, 1961. pp. 41, 46. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>Tiegel, Eliot. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1968/Billboard%201968-06-01.pdf 2 L.A. Outlets Come on Strong]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. June 1, 1968. p. 22. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1973/Billboard%201973-08-25.pdf Radio Stations Enjoy 'Strings']\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. August 25, 1973. pp. A-8, A-12. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"BCYearbook1977\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1977/C%20Section%20Radio%20Broadcasting%20Yearbook%201977%20P-6.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1977]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1977. p. C-22. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In the late 1970s, the station switched to a [[soft adult contemporary]] format.<ref>Herbeck, Ray, Jr. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1978/Billboard%201978-11-11.pdf Buses Prove Promo Boon To L.A. Outlets]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. November 11, 1978. p. 40. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In August 1978, it began carrying the [[radio syndication|syndicated]] ''[[Larry King Show]]'' overnight.<ref>Moran, Bill. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-01-20.pdf MOR /Adult Contemporary Now Cutting Back Night Music Shows]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. January 20, 1979. p. 32. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref>\n\n===KZLA===\nIn 1979, the station's call sign was changed to '''KZLA''' while airing a more upbeat [[adult contemporary]] format, [[simulcast]] with 93.9 KZLA-FM.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=45930 History Cards for KMPC], fcc.gov. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-10-13.pdf L.A. KPOL Is Now KZLA]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. October 13, 1979. p. 22. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>  But with several other AC stations in Los Angeles, KZLA-AM-FM had trouble achieving significant ratings.\n\nIn 1980, with no [[country music]] station on FM in Los Angeles, KZLA-AM-FM flipped to a country format.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/80s/1980/BB-1980-09-27.pdf Los Angeles Now Boasting 4 Country Format Stations]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. September 27, 1980. pp. 3, 21, 43. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Spanish language era===\nIn 1984, the station was sold to [[Spanish Broadcasting System]] for $5 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1984/BC-1984-08-20.pdf Changing Hands]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. August 20, 1984. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In December 1984, the station's call sign was changed to '''KSKQ''', and it adopted a [[Spanish language]] format as \"La Super KQ\".<ref name=\"CallSign\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=61647&Callsign=KMPC61647 Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1985/RR-1985-01-11.pdf Street Talk]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. January 11, 1985. p. 30. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>McDougal, Dennis. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-04-06-ca-4427-story.html Radio In the Afternoon]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. April 6, 1986. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref> \n\nOn August 4, 1992, its call sign was changed to '''KXED''', and it aired a [[Mexican pop music|Mexican pop/contemporary]] format branded \"La Grande\" or The Big One.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/><ref>Stark, Phyllis; Boehlert, Eric; Borzillo, Carrie. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-08-22.pdf Vox Jox]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. August 22, 1992. p. 75. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref> On March 29, 1996, the station's call sign was changed to '''KXMG'''.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> In late 1996, its format was changed from [[Regional Mexican]] to [[Spanish oldies]].<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1996-12.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 13, No. 49. December 4, 1996. p. 1. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Sports era===\nIn 1997, One on One Sports Inc. of [[Northbrook, Illinois|Northbrook]], [[Illinois]], purchased the station and changed its format to [[sports radio|sports]], as an owned-and-operated [[network affiliate]] of [[SB Nation Radio|One-on-One Sports]], later known as Sporting News Radio, a nationally syndicated 24/7 sports network.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1997/RR-1997-10-10.pdf One-On-One Sports Closes Station Deals]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. October 10, 1997. p. 8. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1997-09.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 14, No. 35. September 3, 1997. p. 1. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref> On December 19, 1997, its call sign was changed to '''KCTD'''.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> One on One Sports also bought AM stations in the [[New York City]] and [[Chicago]] areas, so it would have its programming available in the largest, second largest and third largest [[media market|radio market]]s.\n\nOn March 28, 2000, the call sign was changed to '''KMPC'''.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> In 2000, One-on-One Sports was acquired by [[Paul Allen]]'s [[Vulcan Inc.|Vulcan Ventures]], and ownership of KMPC was transferred to Paul Allen's [[Rose City Radio Corporation]].<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2000/RR-2000-12-15.pdf Vulcan Prospers With One-On-One Deal]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. December 15, 2000. p. 6. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=555827&File_number=BAL-20010313AAE Public Notice Comment \u2013 BAL-20010313AAE], fcc.gov. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>  The KMPC call letters had long been used in Los Angeles on [[AM 710]] (now [[KSPN (AM)|KSPN]]).  On February 10, 2003, the station began to be branded \"1540 The Ticket\", concurrent with the launch of a new local morning show, hosted by [[Roger Lodge]].<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.1540theticket.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030209172556/http://www.1540theticket.com/|title=Roger Lodge & the NEW 1540 The Ticket Debuts Monday Feb. 10th|publisher=KMPC |archive-date=February 9, 2003 |accessdate=May 1, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe station covered Southern California sports teams, including the [[San Diego Chargers]].<ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/>  It also aired select [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]] sports programming not carried by [[CBS Radio]]'s [[KFWB (AM)|KFWB]] and [[KAMP-FM|KLSX]].  Among the many Westwood One games KMPC carried include [[NCAA]] basketball, [[PGA Tour]] golf tournament updates (mostly those covered by [[CBS Sports]] television), the [[Masters Tournament]] and [[NFL]] football (including [[Monday Night Football]] on occasion).\n\nIn 2006, KMPC lost the broadcast rights to [[University of Southern California]] [[USC Trojans|Trojans basketball and football]] to rival 710 [[KSPN (AM)|KSPN]].  KMPC acquired the local broadcast rights of the [[University of Notre Dame]]'s football games from [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]].  The station also stopped covering [[NASCAR]] races after having done so for several years.\n \nThe station's regular talk-show hosts included [[Tony Bruno]], who began his morning show in April 2005 following the departure of Roger Lodge;<ref name\"Stewart32505\">Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-mar-25-sp-tvcol25-story.html Bruno's Return Could Be KMPC's Ticket to Success]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. March 25, 2005. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/> Dave Smith,<ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/><ref>Roderick, Kevin. \"[http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2005/08/the_lowedown.php The Lowe-down]\", ''LAObserved''. August 3, 2005. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref> [[Fred Roggin]],<ref>Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-dec-05-sp-11635-story.html Roggin to Host Radio Show]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. December 5, 2001. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Stewart52805\"/> and former USC football player [[Petros Papadakis]].<ref>Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-aug-31-sp-40460-story.html Papadakis Talks a Great Game]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. August 31, 2001. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref>Hoffarth, Tom. \"[https://www.dailynews.com/2006/01/13/loud-and-proud/ Loud and proud]\", ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]''. January 13, 2006. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nFormer Los Angeles Dodgers broadcaster [[Ross Porter (American broadcaster)|Ross Porter]] filled in for Roggin in May 2005.<ref name=\"Stewart52805\">Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-may-28-sp-briefing28-story.html Impressive, but It's Not Rocket Science]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. May 28, 2005. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nRoger Nadel, former GM of all-news [[KFWB]] in Los Angeles, was General Manager.<ref name=\"AAMG101906\"/><ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/><ref name=\"BCYearbook2006\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2006/Radio-All-%20BC-YB-2006.pdf Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2006]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable]], 2006. p. D-81. Retrieved May 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, former afternoon host and [[KNBC-TV]] sports director Fred Roggin left KMPC, resulting in a shift in the station's daily programming lineup and the addition of a new program, the [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]-based [[2 Live Stews]].<ref>\"[https://www.ocregister.com/2006/06/11/radio-stardate-explains-the-night/ Radio: 'StarDate' explains the night]\", ''[[Orange County Register]]''. June 11, 2006. Retrieved May 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2006, it was announced that [[Sporting News Radio]] would be sold to [[American City Business Journals]] for an undisclosed price.<ref>\"[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14684609/ns/business-us_business/t/paul-allens-vulcan-unloads-sporting-news/ Paul Allen's Vulcan unloads The Sporting News]\", [[Associated Press]]. [[NBC News]]. September 5, 2006. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/stories/2006/09/04/daily4.html American City Business Journals buys Sporting News magazine]\", ''[[Birmingham Business Journal]]''. September 5, 2006. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In October 2006, the station fired all local on-air staff.<ref name=\"Stewart101906\">Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-oct-19-sp-tvshort19-story.html All Local KMPC Employees Fired]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. October 19, 2006. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"AAMG101906\">\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/15847/kmpc-l-a-drops-local-staff KMPC/L.A. Drops Local Staff]\", ''All Access Music Group''. October 19, 2006. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Radio Korea===\nIn 2007, the station was sold to P&Y Broadcasting for $33 million, and it began to air [[Korean language]] programming as \"Radio Korea\".<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2007/RR-2007-04-20.pdf Deal of the Week]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. April 20, 2007. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/23684/kmpc-price-33-million KMPC Price: $33 Million]\", ''All Access Music Group''. April 12, 2007. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2007-may-04-sp-tvcol4-story.html Can the fight match hype?]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. May 4, 2007. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In April 2013, KMPC began airing Korean language broadcasts of [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] [[MLB|baseball]] games.<ref>\"[https://www.mlb.com/dodgers/news/dodgers-announce-official-korean-radio-partner-radio-korea/c-43728150 Dodgers announce official Korean radio partner Radio Korea]\", [[MLB.com]]. April 2, 2013. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.radiokorea.com Radio Korea Website] {{in lang|ko}}\n{{AM station data|KMPC}}\n*[http://www.tonybrunoshow.com Tony Bruno Show]\n\n{{Los Angeles Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Korean-American culture in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Los Angeles|MPC]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1952]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Korean-language radio stations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Korean&ndash;language radio station in Los Angeles}}\n{{For|the Los Angeles station formerly known as KMPC at 710 kHz|KSPN (AM)}}\n<!-- RK was launched in February 1989 on KZAN 1300 AM -->\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = KMPC\n| image            = File:KMPC radiokorea logo.jpg\n| city             = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| area             = [[Greater Los Angeles area|Greater Los Angeles]]\n| branding         = ''Radio Korea''\n| slogan           = \n| frequency        = 1540 ([[Kilohertz|kHz]])\n| repeater         = \n| airdate          = September 22, [[1952 in radio|1952]]<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/Section-B-Radio-Broadcasting-Yearbook-1971-;11.pdf 1971 Broadcasting Yearbook]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1971. p. B-;22. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref>\n| format           = [[Korean language|Korean programming]]\n| power            = 50,000 [[watt]]s (day)<br>37,000 watts (night)\n| class            = B\n| facility_id      = 61647\n| coordinates      = {{coord|34|4|43|N|118|11|5|W|region:US-CA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| callsign_meaning = K '''M'''ultilingual '''P'''rogramming '''C'''orporation\n| former_callsigns = KPOL (1952&ndash;1979)<br>KZLA (1979&ndash;1984)<br>KSKQ (1984&ndash;1992)<br>KXED (1992&ndash;1996)<br>KXMG (1996&ndash;1997)<br>KCTD (1997&ndash;2000)\n| affiliations     = \n| owner            = P&Y Broadcasting Corporation\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  = \n| webcast          = \n| website          = [http://www.radiokorea.com/ radiokorea.com]\n}}\n'''KMPC''' (1540 [[Hertz|kHz]], \"Radio Korea\", \ub77c\ub514\uc624\ucf54\ub9ac\uc544) is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[AM radio|AM]] [[radio station]] in [[Los Angeles, California]].  It is owned by P&Y Broadcasting Corporation.  Radio Korea is a division of the Radio Korea Media Group.  The station airs Korean&ndash;language programming, a blend of talk, news, information, and music for the largest [[Korean&ndash;American]] community in the [[United States]], and the largest [[Koreans|Korean]] community outside Korea.  KMPC is one of four radio stations in the greater [[Los Angeles]] area that broadcast entirely in Korean.  The others are 1190 [[KGBN]] [[Anaheim]], 1230 [[KYPA]] Los Angeles and 1650 [[KFOX (AM)|KFOX]] [[Torrance, California|Torrance]].\n\nKMPC broadcasts at 50,000 [[watt]]s by day, the highest power permitted for commercial AM stations.  At night, to reduce interference to other stations on [[AM 1540]], KMPC drops its power to 37,000 watts.  It uses a [[directional antenna]] at all times.  The [[transmitter]] is off Carter Drive in the [[El Sereno, Los Angeles|El Sereno]] district of Los Angeles.<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/finder?sr=Y&s=C&call=Kmpc&nav= Radio-Locator.com/KMPC]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===KPOL===\nOn September 22, 1952, the station [[sign-on|signed on]] with the [[call sign]] '''KPOL'''.<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\" /> It ran 5,000 watts and was originally a [[daytimer]], required to be off the air at sunset.  It was owned by Coast Radio Broadcasting Corporation.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" />  In 1958, it added an FM station at 93.9 MHz, KPOL-FM (now [[KLLI (FM)|KLLI]]).  Then in 1965, it put a television station on the air, Channel 22 KPOL-TV (now [[KWHY-TV]]).\n\nKPOL 1540 went on the air 10 minutes after receiving [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) approval.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31511041/kttv_telecasts_eisenhower_talk_tonight/ |title=KTTV Telecasts Eisenhower Talk Tonight; NBC, CBS Race for TV City Opening Honors |last=Ames |first=Walter |date=1952-09-25 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2019-05-13 |language=en}}</ref> The following year, its power was increased to 10,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" /> Full time operations were added in 1958, with a power of 10,000 watts at night using a directional [[antenna array]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" /> Daytime power was increased to 50,000 watts in 1961.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\" />\n\nIn its early years, KPOL aired several [[polka music]] programs.<ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Life/50s/Radio-TV-Life-1953-01-09.pdf TV-Radio Life]''. January 10-16, 1953. Retrieved April 29, 2019</ref> That gave the station its call letters.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/31510903/new_radio_station_goes_on_air_today/ |title=New Radio Station Goes on Air Today; KPOL to Transmit Over Frequency of 1540 Kilocycles |date=1952-09-15 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2019-05-13 |language=en}}</ref> [[Tom Kennedy (television host)|Tom Kennedy]], later a popular TV [[game show]] host, was a polka DJ on the station during this era.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Baber|first1=David|title=Television Game Show Hosts: Biographies of 32 Stars|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-1-4766-0480-0|page=133|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VbrwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA133#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 29, 2019|date=2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, KPOL advertised on a billboard at Los Angeles's [[Wrigley Field (Los Angeles)|Wrigley Field]], which can be seen in the [[television series]] ''[[Home Run Derby (TV series)|Home Run Derby]]''.\n\nIn 1966, KPOL-AM-FM were sold to [[Capital Cities/ABC Inc.|Capital Cities Broadcasting]] for $7.8 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1966/1966-07-25-BC.pdf KPOL buy brings Capital up to limit]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. July 25, 1966. p. 58. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"HistoryCards\" />\n\nFor many years, KPOL aired an [[easy listening]]/[[beautiful music]] format on both AM and FM.<ref>Zhito, Lee. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1961/Billboard%201961-02-27.pdf LP Programming]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. February 27, 1961. pp. 41, 46. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>Tiegel, Eliot. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1968/Billboard%201968-06-01.pdf 2 L.A. Outlets Come on Strong]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. June 1, 1968. p. 22. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1973/Billboard%201973-08-25.pdf Radio Stations Enjoy 'Strings']\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. August 25, 1973. pp. A-8, A-12. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"BCYearbook1977\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1977/C%20Section%20Radio%20Broadcasting%20Yearbook%201977%20P-6.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1977]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1977. p. C-22. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In the late 1970s, the station switched to a [[soft adult contemporary]] format.<ref>Herbeck, Ray, Jr. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1978/Billboard%201978-11-11.pdf Buses Prove Promo Boon To L.A. Outlets]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. November 11, 1978. p. 40. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In August 1978, it began carrying the [[radio syndication|syndicated]] ''[[Larry King Show]]'' overnight.<ref>Moran, Bill. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-01-20.pdf MOR /Adult Contemporary Now Cutting Back Night Music Shows]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. January 20, 1979. p. 32. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref>\n\n===KZLA===\nIn 1979, the station's call sign was changed to '''KZLA''' while airing a more upbeat [[adult contemporary]] format, [[simulcast]] with 93.9 KZLA-FM.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=45930 History Cards for KMPC], fcc.gov. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-10-13.pdf L.A. KPOL Is Now KZLA]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. October 13, 1979. p. 22. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>  But with several other AC stations in Los Angeles, KZLA-AM-FM had trouble achieving significant ratings.\n\nIn 1980, with no [[country music]] station on FM in Los Angeles, KZLA-AM-FM flipped to a country format.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/80s/1980/BB-1980-09-27.pdf Los Angeles Now Boasting 4 Country Format Stations]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. September 27, 1980. pp. 3, 21, 43. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Spanish language era===\nIn 1984, the station was sold to [[Spanish Broadcasting System]] for $5 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1984/BC-1984-08-20.pdf Changing Hands]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. August 20, 1984. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In December 1984, the station's call sign was changed to '''KSKQ''', and it adopted a [[Spanish language]] format as \"La Super KQ\".<ref name=\"CallSign\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=61647&Callsign=KMPC61647 Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1985/RR-1985-01-11.pdf Street Talk]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. January 11, 1985. p. 30. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>McDougal, Dennis. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-04-06-ca-4427-story.html Radio In the Afternoon]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. April 6, 1986. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref> \n\nOn August 4, 1992, its call sign was changed to '''KXED''', and it aired a [[Mexican pop music|Mexican pop/contemporary]] format branded \"La Grande\" or The Big One.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/><ref>Stark, Phyllis; Boehlert, Eric; Borzillo, Carrie. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-08-22.pdf Vox Jox]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. August 22, 1992. p. 75. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref> On March 29, 1996, the station's call sign was changed to '''KXMG'''.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> In late 1996, its format was changed from [[Regional Mexican]] to [[Spanish oldies]].<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1996-12.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 13, No. 49. December 4, 1996. p. 1. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Sports era===\nIn 1997, One on One Sports Inc. of [[Northbrook, Illinois|Northbrook]], [[Illinois]], purchased the station and changed its format to [[sports radio|sports]], as an owned-and-operated [[network affiliate]] of [[SB Nation Radio|One-on-One Sports]], later known as Sporting News Radio, a nationally syndicated 24/7 sports network.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1997/RR-1997-10-10.pdf One-On-One Sports Closes Station Deals]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. October 10, 1997. p. 8. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1997-09.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 14, No. 35. September 3, 1997. p. 1. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref> On December 19, 1997, its call sign was changed to '''KCTD'''.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> One on One Sports also bought AM stations in the [[New York City]] and [[Chicago]] areas, so it would have its programming available in the largest, second largest and third largest [[media market|radio market]]s.\n\nOn March 28, 2000, the call sign was changed to '''KMPC'''.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> In 2000, One-on-One Sports was acquired by [[Paul Allen]]'s [[Vulcan Inc.|Vulcan Ventures]], and ownership of KMPC was transferred to Paul Allen's [[Rose City Radio Corporation]].<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2000/RR-2000-12-15.pdf Vulcan Prospers With One-On-One Deal]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. December 15, 2000. p. 6. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=555827&File_number=BAL-20010313AAE Public Notice Comment \u2013 BAL-20010313AAE], fcc.gov. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref>  The KMPC call letters had long been used in Los Angeles on [[AM 710]] (now [[KSPN (AM)|KSPN]]).  On February 10, 2003, the station began to be branded \"1540 The Ticket\", concurrent with the launch of a new local morning show, hosted by [[Roger Lodge]].<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.1540theticket.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030209172556/http://www.1540theticket.com/|title=Roger Lodge & the NEW 1540 The Ticket Debuts Monday Feb. 10th|publisher=KMPC |archive-date=February 9, 2003 |accessdate=May 1, 2019 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe station covered Southern California sports teams, including the [[San Diego Chargers]].<ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/>  It also aired select [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]] sports programming not carried by [[CBS Radio]]'s [[KFWB (AM)|KFWB]] and [[KAMP-FM|KLSX]].  Among the many Westwood One games KMPC carried include [[NCAA]] basketball, [[PGA Tour]] golf tournament updates (mostly those covered by [[CBS Sports]] television), the [[Masters Tournament]] and [[NFL]] football (including [[Monday Night Football]] on occasion).\n\nIn 2006, KMPC lost the broadcast rights to [[University of Southern California]] [[USC Trojans|Trojans basketball and football]] to rival 710 [[KSPN (AM)|KSPN]].  KMPC acquired the local broadcast rights of the [[University of Notre Dame]]'s football games from [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]].  The station also stopped covering [[NASCAR]] races after having done so for several years.\n \nThe station's regular talk-show hosts included [[Tony Bruno]], who began his morning show in April 2005 following the departure of Roger Lodge;<ref name\"Stewart32505\">Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-mar-25-sp-tvcol25-story.html Bruno's Return Could Be KMPC's Ticket to Success]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. March 25, 2005. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/> Dave Smith,<ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/><ref>Roderick, Kevin. \"[http://www.laobserved.com/archive/2005/08/the_lowedown.php The Lowe-down]\", ''LAObserved''. August 3, 2005. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref> [[Fred Roggin]],<ref>Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-dec-05-sp-11635-story.html Roggin to Host Radio Show]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. December 5, 2001. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Stewart52805\"/> and former USC football player [[Petros Papadakis]].<ref>Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-aug-31-sp-40460-story.html Papadakis Talks a Great Game]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. August 31, 2001. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref>Hoffarth, Tom. \"[https://www.dailynews.com/2006/01/13/loud-and-proud/ Loud and proud]\", ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]''. January 13, 2006. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nFormer Los Angeles Dodgers broadcaster [[Ross Porter (American broadcaster)|Ross Porter]] filled in for Roggin in May 2005.<ref name=\"Stewart52805\">Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-may-28-sp-briefing28-story.html Impressive, but It's Not Rocket Science]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. May 28, 2005. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\nRoger Nadel, former GM of all-news [[KFWB]] in Los Angeles, was General Manager.<ref name=\"AAMG101906\"/><ref name=\"Stewart101906\"/><ref name=\"BCYearbook2006\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2006/Radio-All-%20BC-YB-2006.pdf Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2006]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable]], 2006. p. D-81. Retrieved May 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, former afternoon host and [[KNBC-TV]] sports director Fred Roggin left KMPC, resulting in a shift in the station's daily programming lineup and the addition of a new program, the [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]-based [[2 Live Stews]].<ref>\"[https://www.ocregister.com/2006/06/11/radio-stardate-explains-the-night/ Radio: 'StarDate' explains the night]\", ''[[Orange County Register]]''. June 11, 2006. Retrieved May 1, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2006, it was announced that [[Sporting News Radio]] would be sold to [[American City Business Journals]] for an undisclosed price.<ref>\"[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14684609/ns/business-us_business/t/paul-allens-vulcan-unloads-sporting-news/ Paul Allen's Vulcan unloads The Sporting News]\", [[Associated Press]]. [[NBC News]]. September 5, 2006. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/stories/2006/09/04/daily4.html American City Business Journals buys Sporting News magazine]\", ''[[Birmingham Business Journal]]''. September 5, 2006. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In October 2006, the station fired all local on-air staff.<ref name=\"Stewart101906\">Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-oct-19-sp-tvshort19-story.html All Local KMPC Employees Fired]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. October 19, 2006. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"AAMG101906\">\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/15847/kmpc-l-a-drops-local-staff KMPC/L.A. Drops Local Staff]\", ''All Access Music Group''. October 19, 2006. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Radio Korea===\nIn 2007, the station was sold to P&Y Broadcasting for $33 million, and it began to air [[Korean language]] programming as \"Radio Korea\".<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2007/RR-2007-04-20.pdf Deal of the Week]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. April 20, 2007. Retrieved April 28, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/23684/kmpc-price-33-million KMPC Price: $33 Million]\", ''All Access Music Group''. April 12, 2007. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref><ref>Stewart, Larry. \"[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2007-may-04-sp-tvcol4-story.html Can the fight match hype?]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. May 4, 2007. Retrieved April 29, 2019.</ref> In April 2013, KMPC began airing Korean language broadcasts of [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] [[MLB|baseball]] games.<ref>\"[https://www.mlb.com/dodgers/news/dodgers-announce-official-korean-radio-partner-radio-korea/c-43728150 Dodgers announce official Korean radio partner Radio Korea]\", [[MLB.com]]. April 2, 2013. Retrieved April 30, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.radiokorea.com Radio Korea Website] {{in lang|ko}}\n{{AM station data|KMPC}}\n*[http://www.tonybrunoshow.com Tony Bruno Show]\n\n{{Los Angeles Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Korean-American culture in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Los Angeles|MPC]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1952]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Korean-language radio stations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Stereorock", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KMPC"}
{"title_page": "Strathrusdale", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |country = Scotland\n |official_name= Strathrusdale\n |gaelic_name= Strath R\u00f9sdail\n |scots_name=\n| population = 30\n| population_ref = (est.)\n  |os_grid_reference= NH6174\n |coordinates = {{coord|57.75|-4.40|display=inline,title}}\n |map_type=Scotland\n |unitary_scotland= [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n |lieutenancy_scotland= [[Ross and Cromarty]]\n |constituency_westminster= [[Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross (UK Parliament constituency)|Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross]]\n |constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Ross, Skye and Inverness West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Inverness West]]\n |post_town= [[Alness]]\n |postcode_district = IV17\n |postcode_area= IV \n |dial_code= 01349\n }}\n{{Campaignbox Conflicts during the Highland Clearances}}\n'''Strathrusdale''' ([[Scottish Gaelic]]/[[Old Norse|Norse]] Hybrid: ''Strath R\u00f9sdail, Strath'', [Gaelic] small '''valley''', of '''Rusdale''', ''rus'', Norse for [male sheep] '''ram''', and '''dale''', also small valley)<ref>Place Names of Ross & Cromarty; W J Watson (1904)</ref> [[Glen]] in the [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]] of [[Scotland]] forming the western part of the area known as  [[Ardross, Highland|Ardross]]. The Strath runs east to west for 2.5 miles and the river Blackwater flows through it to merge at the eastern end with another tributary to form the River Alness. The floor of the strath is mainly fields used for sheep grazing. The strath is surrounded by commercial pine forest, except to the north, which is dominated by the mountain [[Beinn Tharsuinn]] (2831&nbsp;ft). Traditionally the strath was populated by tenant crofters, however in recent years there has been an increase in the number of new homes and restorations, after many decades of gradual decline.\n\n== History ==\n\n===The Picts===\nEarliest evidence of habitation are still visible in Strathrusdale at the eastern end of the Strath, where there are a number of stone circles, which formed the base of Pictish [[roundhouse (dwelling)|roundhouses]]. [[Picts]] lived in the area until the 10th century, which was part of the [[Kingdom of Fortriu]]. After this period there was progressively more transition as Norse settlement began to increase in the area.\n\n===Highland Clearances===\nDuring the late 18th century, great change swept the Highlands when landowners realised that more income could be generated by clearing areas farmed by tenant crofters to make way for sheep. Termed the [[Highland Clearances]], this coincided with a period of great unrest and social upheaval in Europe which unsettled the authorities in Britain.\n\nStrathrusdale became the focus of the clearance policy in 1792 when on the 27th of July the inhabitants of the strath gathered for a wedding in the area where a plot was devised to drive away all the sheep, and by implication all the sheep-farmers. This issue had arose when in May, 1792, the brothers Captain Allan and Alexander Cameron who were leasing the neighboring lands of Kildermorie from [[Hector Munro, 8th laird of Novar]] had driven away the cattle belonging to the Strathrusdale people.<ref name=\"Transactions\">{{cite web |url=https://electricscotland.com/history/articles/sheep.htm |title=The Year of the Sheep |website=electricscotland.com |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |quote=From the Transactions of the Gaelic Society of Inverness}}</ref> The men of Strathrusdale had gatherred reinforcements from [[Ardross, Highland|Ardross]] and upon arriving at Kildermorie found their cattle was being guarded by the Camerons. The Strathrusdale men were led by Alexander Wallace, known as \"Big Wallace\" and although the Camerons were powerful men they were too few in number and had to yield. However, one of the Camerons was armed with a loaded gun and a foot long [[dirk]]. Wallace grappled with him, disarmed him and the Strathrusdale men recovered their cattle.<ref name=\"Transactions\"/>  A week after the meeting of 27th July, about 400 men from the surrounding districts were driving six thousand sheep from the counties of [[Ross, Scotland|Ross]] and [[Sutherland]] towards [[Beauly]] in the county of [[Inverness-shire]]. The sheriff-depute of the county, Donald MacLeod, wrote to the Lord Advocate, asking that a force of the [[42nd Regiment of Foot|42nd (Black Watch) Regiment]] from the army be sent north to defeat what MacLeod viewed as open rebellion.<ref name=\"BBCNews2011\">{{cite news |date=June 13, 2011 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-13747435 |title=Fort George built to silence rebel yell |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Lord Advocate wrote to the Home Secretary [[Henry Dundas, 1st Viscount Melville|Henry Dundas]] reporting that sheep farming was very unpopular in the Highlands, as it \u2018tended to remove the inhabitants from their small possessions and dwelling houses\u2019.  The Home Secretary replied that it was \u2018undisputably necessary that the most vigorous and effectual measures should be taken for bringing these daring offenders to punishment\u2019 - and ordered troops north. After a midnight attack on Saturday 6 August by troops of the 42nd Black Watch, the drovers scattered and returned to their crofts.<ref name=\"Transactions\"/> The Inverness County Sheriff Court Records show that six men were given punishments for driving the sheep away: Hugh Breck Mackenzie and John Aird were both ordered to be transported for seven years \"beyond seas to such places as His Majesty shall appoint\" and that if they returned to Britian within these seven years that they would be sentenced to death. Malcolm Ross was fined \u00a350 and held in prison for one month, while William Cunningham was imprisoned for three years. Donald Munro and Alexander Mackay were both banished from Scotland for the rest of their lives.<ref name=\"BBCNews2009\">{{cite news |last=Mckenzie |first=Steven |date=May 21, 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/highlands_and_islands/8061285.stm |title=Banished for driving sheep away |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> These events were known as the Ross-shire Sheep Riots but later became known as ''The Year of the Sheep''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ambaile.org.uk/detail/en/5757/1/EN5757-petition-of-the-ross-family-to-lord.htm |title=Petition of the Ross family to Lord Stonefield |website=ambaile.org.uk |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nStrathrusdale 02.jpg|Strathrusdale looking west\nStrathrusdale 03.jpg|Access road on northern side of glen\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n<!--<nowiki>\n  See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how\n  to generate footnotes using the<ref> and </ref> tags, and the template below \n</nowiki>-->\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Valleys of Highland (council area)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |country = Scotland\n |official_name= Strathrusdale\n |gaelic_name= Strath R\u00f9sdail\n |scots_name=\n| population = 30\n| population_ref = (est.)\n  |os_grid_reference= NH6174\n |coordinates = {{coord|57.75|-4.40|display=inline,title}}\n |map_type=Scotland\n |unitary_scotland= [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n |lieutenancy_scotland= [[Ross and Cromarty]]\n |constituency_westminster= [[Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross (UK Parliament constituency)|Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross]]\n |constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Ross, Skye and Inverness West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Inverness West]]\n |post_town= [[Alness]]\n |postcode_district = IV17\n |postcode_area= IV \n |dial_code= 01349\n }}\n{{Campaignbox Conflicts during the Highland Clearances}}\n'''Strathrusdale''' ([[Scottish Gaelic]]/[[Old Norse|Norse]] Hybrid: ''Strath R\u00f9sdail, Strath'', [Gaelic] small '''valley''', of '''Rusdale''', ''rus'', Norse for [male sheep] '''ram''', and '''dale''', also small valley)<ref>Place Names of Ross & Cromarty; W J Watson (1904)</ref> [[Glen]] in the [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]] of [[Scotland]] forming the western part of the area known as  [[Ardross, Highland|Ardross]]. The Strath runs east to west for 2.5 miles and the river Blackwater flows through it to merge at the eastern end with another tributary to form the River Alness. The floor of the strath is mainly fields used for sheep grazing. The strath is surrounded by commercial pine forest, except to the north, which is dominated by the mountain [[Beinn Tharsuinn]] (2831&nbsp;ft). Traditionally the strath was populated by tenant crofters, however in recent years there has been an increase in the number of new homes and restorations, after many decades of gradual decline.\n\n== History ==\n\n===The Picts===\nEarliest evidence of habitation are still visible in Strathrusdale at the eastern end of the Strath, where there are a number of stone circles, which formed the base of Pictish [[roundhouse (dwelling)|roundhouses]]. [[Picts]] lived in the area until the 10th century, which was part of the [[Kingdom of Fortriu]]. After this period there was progressively more transition as Norse settlement began to increase in the area.\n\n===Highland Clearances===\nDuring the late 18th century, great change swept the Highlands when landowners realised that more income could be generated by clearing areas farmed by tenant crofters to make way for sheep. Termed the [[Highland Clearances]], this coincided with a period of great unrest and social upheaval in Europe which unsettled the authorities in Britain.\n\nStrathrusdale became the focus of the clearance policy in 1792 when on the 27th of July the inhabitants of the strath gathered for a wedding in the area where a plot was devised to drive away all the sheep, and by implication all the sheep-farmers. This issue had arose when in May, 1792, the brothers Captain Allan and Alexander Cameron who were leasing the neighboring lands of Kildermorie from [[Hector Munro, 8th laird of Novar]] had driven away the cattle belonging to the Strathrusdale people.<ref name=\"Transactions\">{{cite web |url=https://electricscotland.com/history/articles/sheep.htm |title=The Year of the Sheep |website=electricscotland.com |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |quote=From the Transactions of the Gaelic Society of Inverness}}</ref> The men of Strathrusdale had gatherred reinforcements from [[Ardross, Highland|Ardross]] and upon arriving at Kildermorie found their cattle was being guarded by the Camerons. The Strathrusdale men were led by Alexander Wallace, known as \"Big Wallace\" and although the Camerons were powerful men they were too few in number and had to yield. However, one of the Camerons was armed with a loaded gun and a foot long [[dirk]]. Wallace grappled with him, disarmed him and the Strathrusdale men recovered their cattle.<ref name=\"Transactions\"/>  A week after the meeting of 27th July, about 400 men from the surrounding districts were driving six thousand sheep from the counties of [[Ross]] and [[Sutherland]] towards [[Beauly]] in the county of [[Inverness-shire]]. The sheriff-depute of the county, Donald MacLeod, wrote to the Lord Advocate, asking that a force of the [[42nd Regiment of Foot|42nd (Black Watch) Regiment]] from the army be sent north to defeat what MacLeod viewed as open rebellion.<ref name=\"BBCNews2011\">{{cite news |date=June 13, 2011 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-13747435 |title=Fort George built to silence rebel yell |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Lord Advocate wrote to the Home Secretary [[Henry Dundas, 1st Viscount Melville|Henry Dundas]] reporting that sheep farming was very unpopular in the Highlands, as it \u2018tended to remove the inhabitants from their small possessions and dwelling houses\u2019.  The Home Secretary replied that it was \u2018undisputably necessary that the most vigorous and effectual measures should be taken for bringing these daring offenders to punishment\u2019 - and ordered troops north. After a midnight attack on Saturday 6 August by troops of the 42nd Black Watch, the drovers scattered and returned to their crofts.<ref name=\"Transactions\"/> The Inverness County Sheriff Court Records show that six men were given punishments for driving the sheep away: Hugh Breck Mackenzie and John Aird were both ordered to be transported for seven years \"beyond seas to such places as His Majesty shall appoint\" and that if they returned to Britian within these seven years that they would be sentenced to death. Malcolm Ross was fined \u00a350 and held in prison for one month, while William Cunningham was imprisoned for three years. Donald Munro and Alexander Mackay were both banished from Scotland for the rest of their lives.<ref name=\"BBCNews2009\">{{cite news |last=Mckenzie |first=Steven |date=May 21, 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/highlands_and_islands/8061285.stm |title=Banished for driving sheep away |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> These events were known as the Ross-shire Sheep Riots but later became known as ''The Year of the Sheep''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ambaile.org.uk/detail/en/5757/1/EN5757-petition-of-the-ross-family-to-lord.htm |title=Petition of the Ross family to Lord Stonefield |website=ambaile.org.uk |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nStrathrusdale 02.jpg|Strathrusdale looking west\nStrathrusdale 03.jpg|Access road on northern side of glen\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n<!--<nowiki>\n  See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how\n  to generate footnotes using the<ref> and </ref> tags, and the template below \n</nowiki>-->\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Valleys of Highland (council area)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambigu